main event: On 15 August 1958 in Long Island, New York, a bright orange, fiery object, possibly 30 feet in length, was observed for 5 minutes. No conclusive explanation was given, but possibilities included a navy jet, turbulent air operation, aircraft in distress, or a meteor.
interesting points: The observation lasted for 5 minutes and described the object as a 30-foot long oblong bright orange fiery fall very high.
The weather at the time of the observation was overcast.
The text contains cryptic handwritten notes such as 'Insqr Coo to pch' and 'Poss AC Hax to hin.'
The report mentions a navy jet out of South Weymouth as a possibility for the observed object.
The observation was made by 6 adults, and the weather was described as fair with specific wind directions and speeds at various altitudes.
The document does not contain any photographs, and the data was deemed incomplete with no admissible conclusion given.
